<h3><span class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"Folding_activation_functions">Folding=
 activation functions</span><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DActivation_function&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D=
"Edit section: Folding activation functions">edit</a><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1033289096"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fold_function" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fold function">Fold function</a></div>
<p>Folding activation functions are extensively used in the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolutional_neural_network#Pooling_layers" titl=
e=3D"Convolutional neural network">pooling layers</a> in <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolutional_neural_network" title=3D"Convolutional=
 neural network">convolutional neural networks</a>, and in output layers of=
 multiclass classification networks. These activations perform aggregation =
over the inputs, such as taking the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Mean" title=3D"Mean">mean</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
inimum" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Minimum">minimum</a> or <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Maximu=
m">maximum</a>. In multiclass classification the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Softmax_function" title=3D"Softmax function">softmax</a> act=
ivation is often used.
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"Comparison_of_activation_functions">C=
omparison of activation functions</span><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DActivation_function&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Comparison of activation functions">edit</a><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>There are numerous activation functions and comprehensive surveys are pr=
ovided in.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Activation_function#cite_note-:0-1">[1]</a></sup><s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-:1_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Activation_function#cite_note-:1-5">[5]</a></sup> Hinton et al.=
's seminal 2012 paper on automatic speech recognition uses a logistic sigmo=
id activation function.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Activation_function#cite_note-6">[6]</a><=
/sup> The seminal 2012 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AlexNet" ti=
tle=3D"AlexNet">AlexNet</a> computer vision architecture uses the ReLU acti=
vation function, as did the seminal 2015 computer vision architecture <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Residual_neural_network" title=3D"Resid=
ual neural network">ResNet</a>. The seminal 2018 language processing model =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BERT_(language_model)" title=3D"BE=
RT (language model)">BERT</a> uses a smooth version of the ReLU, the GELU.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-ReferenceA_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Activation_function#cite_note-ReferenceA-7">[7]</a></s=
up>
</p><p>Aside from their empirical performance, activation functions also ha=
ve different mathematical properties:
</p>
<dl><dt>Nonlinear</dt>
<dd>When the activation function is non-linear, then a two-layer neural net=
work can be proven to be a universal function approximator.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Activat=
ion_function#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup> This is known as the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_approximation_theorem" title=3D"Univer=
sal approximation theorem">Universal Approximation Theorem</a>. The identit=
y activation function does not satisfy this property. When multiple layers =
use the identity activation function, the entire network is equivalent to a=
 single-layer model.</dd>
<dt>Range</dt>
<dd>When the range of the activation function is finite, gradient-based tra=
ining methods tend to be more stable, because pattern presentations signifi=
cantly affect only limited weights. When the range is infinite, training is=
 generally more efficient because pattern presentations significantly affec=
t most of the weights. In the latter case, smaller <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Learning_rate" title=3D"Learning rate">learning rates</a> =
are typically necessary.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact=
" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span titl=
e=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (January 2016)">citat=
ion needed</span></a></i>]</sup></dd>
<dt>Continuously differentiable</dt>
<dd>This property is desirable (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Re=
ctifier_(neural_networks)" title=3D"Rectifier (neural networks)">ReLU</a> i=
s not continuously differentiable and has some issues with gradient-based o=
ptimization, but it is still possible) for enabling gradient-based optimiza=
tion methods. The binary step activation function is not differentiable at =
0, and it differentiates to 0 for all other values, so gradient-based metho=
ds can make no progress with it.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Activation_function#cite_note-9">[=
9]</a></sup></dd></dl>
<p>These properties do not decisively influence performance, nor are they t=
he only mathematical properties that may be useful. For instance, the stric=
tly positive range of the softplus makes it suitable for predicting varianc=
es in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autoencoder#Variational_auto=
encoder_(VAE)" title=3D"Autoencoder">variational autoencoders</a>.
</p>
